Reference-contexts: 1 INTRODUCTION A correspondence between evolutionary algorithms and heuristic state space search is developed in <ref> (Jones, 1995b) </ref>. This is based on a model of fitness landscapes as directed, labeled graphs that are closely related to the state spaces employed in heuristic search. We examine one aspect of this correspondence, the relationship between the fitness functions of GAs and heuristic functions. <p> This indicates that fitnesses tend to increase with distance from the global optimum. In these functions, r does not change when several copies of one of the functions are concatenated to make a longer problem, as is commonly done (this invariance is proved in <ref> (Jones, 1995b) </ref>). The scatter plots of these problems show an interesting additive structure. Figures 2 (a) to 2 (c) show one to three copies of Deb and Gold-berg's function and Figures 2 (e) to 2 (g) show one to three copies of Whitley's F2 function.
